{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493023"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.06,0.02,0.01,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1203"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance after striking his head on the ground during a street fight. Witnesses state that he appeared to lose consciousness for a couple of minutes, but was then able to get up and continue the argument, however several minutes later he became confused and collapsed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 65/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 10/min and SpO2 99% on room air. Cardiorespiratory examination is normal. Neurological assessment reveals that he will not open his eyes even when a trapezius squeeze is performed. He is making sounds that are not words, and he responds to a painful stimulus by withdrawing from the stimulus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT head","Intravenous mannitol","Intravenous dexamethasone","Oxygen by face mask","Endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a Glasgow Coma Score (GCS) of 7/15 (1/4 for eyes, 2/5 for verbal, and 4/6 for motor). Following the ABCDE approach to trauma management, airway is always the first priority, especially in patients with decreased level of consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step because the patient has a GCS less than 8, which indicates he cannot protect his airway. The principle of \u0022GCS 8 = intubate\u0022 is a well-established guideline in emergency medicine. With a GCS of 7, this patient is at high risk of airway compromise, aspiration, and inadequate ventilation. Securing a definitive airway takes precedence over all other interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT head\u003C/strong\u003E is certainly indicated in this patient given the history of head trauma, loss of consciousness with a lucid interval (suggesting possible epidural haematoma), and subsequent deterioration. However, airway management must be secured before transporting the patient for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for reducing intracranial pressure in traumatic brain injury, but it should only be used after imaging confirms intracranial pathology and when there are signs of herniation or progressive neurological deterioration. It is not appropriate as the next step before securing the airway and obtaining imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen by face mask\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient in this scenario. While the patient currently has adequate oxygen saturation, his depressed level of consciousness indicates he cannot protect his airway, making supplemental oxygen alone inadequate and potentially dangerous without a secured airway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E has been shown to increase mortality in traumatic brain injury and is contraindicated in this setting. Current evidence does not support the use of corticosteroids in the management of traumatic brain injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 8 or less require endotracheal intubation to protect the airway.","The ABCDE approach prioritizes airway management as the first step in any emergency situation.","Traumatic brain injury with loss of consciousness followed by a lucid interval suggests an epidural haematoma."],"references":["Haddad SH, Arabi YM. Critical care management of severe traumatic brain injury in adults. Scand J Trauma Resusc Emerg Med. 2012;20:12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22304785/","Alderson P, Roberts I. Corticosteroids for acute traumatic brain injury. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2005 Jan 25;2005(1):CD000196. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9224126/#:~:text=Conclusions%3A%20This%20systematic%20review%20of,harmful%20effects%20can%20be%20excluded."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-09T17:44:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-09T17:44:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1493"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Traumatic brain injury","synonyms":["TBI","Head injury","Concussion"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-12-17T09:54:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T09:07:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4961","links":{"sel